---
import ProjectLayout from '../../layouts/ProjectLayout.astro';
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL.replace(/\/$/, '');
---
<ProjectLayout
  title="Towards a Sustainable City Policy for Managing Shared Dockless E-Scooters"
  year="2024"
  section="Data Science & Analysis"
  category="Procedia Computer Science · ABMTRANS 2024, Hasselt"
  tools={['Python', 'POPULUS / MDS', 'GeoPandas', 'TAZ Analysis', 'GIS']}
>

  <section class="proj-section">
    <h2 class="proj-section-title">Background</h2>
    <div class="proj-body">
      <p>
        Shared dockless e-scooter operators have a structural incentive to cluster their fleets
        in dense, high-demand city centers — leaving peripheral neighborhoods chronically
        underserved. This paper, published in <em>Procedia Computer Science</em> (ABMTRANS 2024),
        investigates whether that mismatch is measurable in Tel Aviv and proposes a data-driven
        policy to correct it.
      </p>
      <p>
        The study draws on an anonymized dataset of <strong>one million shared scooter rides</strong>
        collected by the Tel Aviv municipality via <strong>POPULUS</strong> across 22 working days
        in March 2023 — covering roughly 7,500 vehicles operated by 5 companies across the city's
        52 km². A complementary dataset of <strong>730,000 application activations</strong> from
        one operator captures what happens when a user opens the app but does not end up riding.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="proj-section">
    <h2 class="proj-section-title">Methodology</h2>
    <ul class="proj-list">
      <li>Combined supply-side data from all five Tel Aviv operators into a single trip-level dataset via the <strong>MDS / POPULUS</strong> feed.</li>
      <li>Used <strong>average parking duration per zone</strong> as a demand proxy: a scooter that is picked up quickly signals high latent demand; one left idle for many hours signals oversupply.</li>
      <li>Aggregated metrics to <strong>Traffic Analysis Zones (TAZ)</strong> to map supply–demand balance across the city at the neighbourhood scale.</li>
      <li>Analysed <strong>730K application activation records</strong> to measure the ride/no-ride decision — specifically, how proximity to the nearest available scooter determines whether users proceed with a trip.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="proj-section">
    <h2 class="proj-section-title">Results</h2>

    <h3 class="proj-subsection-title">Figure 2 — Demand heterogeneity across the city</h3>
    <img
      src={`${base}/maps/scooter-policy-fig2.png`}
      alt="Three-panel figure: (a) TAZ map of average scooter parking duration across Tel Aviv — darker zones in the center indicate higher turnover and demand; (b) distribution of all parking durations showing many scooters idle for half a day or more; (c) bar chart showing parking duration drops by nearly an hour when scooters are within 5m of a bike path"
      class="proj-map"
      loading="lazy"
    />
    <p class="proj-map-caption">
      Figure 2. Average parking duration by TAZ (a) reveals that demand is concentrated in the center
      and falls sharply toward the periphery. Panel (b) shows many scooters sitting idle for 6–12+
      hours — a strong oversupply signal. Panel (c) shows proximity to a bike path cuts idle time
      by almost an hour, especially in the center where cycling infrastructure is densest.
    </p>

    <h3 class="proj-subsection-title">Figure 3 — Where supply exceeds demand, and where it falls short</h3>
    <img
      src={`${base}/maps/scooter-policy-fig3.png`}
      alt="Two maps side by side: (a) density of scooters parked longer than 12 hours — hotspots concentrated in the central tourist and commercial areas indicating oversupply; (b) density of scooters parked less than 30 minutes — more spatially dispersed, indicating where active demand is highest"
      class="proj-map"
      loading="lazy"
    />
    <p class="proj-map-caption">
      Figure 3. Scooters idle for more than 12 hours (a) pile up in the central tourist and commercial
      zones — clear oversupply. Scooters turned over within 30 minutes (b) are more dispersed but
      absent from large peripheral stretches, where demand exists but is starved of supply. We
      attribute this pattern to a <em>Mohring-like feedback</em>: operators concentrate in the
      center to guarantee profit, which erodes demand at the periphery through chronic unavailability.
    </p>

    <h3 class="proj-subsection-title">Figure 6 — The ride/no-ride decision and its spatial footprint</h3>
    <img
      src={`${base}/maps/scooter-policy-fig6.png`}
      alt="Five-panel figure: (a) histogram showing 95% of rides start within 110m of the chosen scooter; (b) 75% of users choose the nearest available scooter; (c) the longer a scooter sits idle, the less likely it is to be chosen; (d) users who find no scooter within 100m abandon the trip in 30%+ of cases; (e) TAZ map of no-ride activation rates — near-zero in the center, 15–25% on the periphery"
      class="proj-map"
      loading="lazy"
    />
    <p class="proj-map-caption">
      Figure 6. The ride decision is highly proximity-driven: 95% of riders choose a scooter within
      110 m (a), 75% take the closest one (b), and older-parked scooters are progressively less
      likely to be chosen (c). When no scooter is within 100 m, more than 30% of activations end
      without a ride (d). Spatially, this no-ride rate is virtually zero in the Tel Aviv center
      but climbs to 15–25% on the periphery (e) — the direct consequence of the supply deficit
      documented in Figure 3.
    </p>

    <div class="proj-body">
      <p>
        Based on this analysis, the paper proposes a citywide policy built on two mechanisms:
        establishing parking cells across all populated areas at no more than 200 m spacing, and
        requiring operators to relocate scooters idle for 8–12+ hours from oversupplied cells to
        undersupplied ones. The policy turns oversupply into a directly observable, actionable
        signal rather than relying on blunt percentage quotas for peripheral districts.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="proj-section">
    <h2 class="proj-section-title">Publication</h2>
    <p class="proj-body">
      Published in <em>Procedia Computer Science</em>, vol. 238, pp. 722–727, as part of the
      13th International Workshop on Agent-based Mobility, Traffic and Transportation Models
      (ABMTRANS 2024), Hasselt, Belgium.
    </p>
    <a
      class="proj-external"
      href="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.procs.2024.06.083"
      target="_blank"
      rel="noopener noreferrer"
    >
      View paper on ScienceDirect →
    </a>
    <a class="proj-download" href={`${base}/Scooters_2024.pdf`} download>
      <svg width="14" height="14" viewBox="0 0 12 12" fill="none" aria-hidden="true">
        <path d="M6 1v7M3.5 5.5L6 8l2.5-2.5M1 10h10" stroke="currentColor"
          stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/>
      </svg>
      Download PDF
    </a>
  </section>

</ProjectLayout>

<style>
  :global(.proj-list) {
    list-style: none;
    padding: 0;
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    gap: 10px;
    max-width: 68ch;
  }
  :global(.proj-list li) {
    font-size: 0.9rem;
    line-height: 1.7;
    color: #2A2A2A;
    padding-left: 1.2em;
    position: relative;
  }
  :global(.proj-list li::before) {
    content: '—';
    position: absolute;
    left: 0;
    color: #3D5E35;
    font-weight: 600;
  }

  .proj-subsection-title {
    font-size: 0.9rem;
    font-weight: 700;
    color: #2A2A2A;
    margin: 28px 0 12px;
    letter-spacing: -0.01em;
  }

  .proj-external {
    display: inline-block;
    margin-top: 12px;
    margin-right: 16px;
    font-size: 0.85rem;
    font-weight: 600;
    color: #3D5E35;
    text-decoration: none;
  }
  .proj-external:hover { text-decoration: underline; }

  .proj-download {
    display: inline-flex;
    align-items: center;
    gap: 8px;
    margin-top: 12px;
    padding: 10px 20px;
    font-size: 0.85rem;
    font-weight: 600;
    color: #F0EAE0;
    background: #3D5E35;
    border-radius: 4px;
    text-decoration: none;
    transition: background 0.15s;
    width: fit-content;
  }
  .proj-download:hover { background: #2E4828; }
</style>
